"lp">Subject</td><td class="rp" itemprop="name">Re: [GIT *] Allow request_firmware() to be satisfied from in-kernel, use it in more drivers.</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody"><br /><br />On Mon, 14 Jul 2008, David Woodhouse wrote:<br />&gt; <br />&gt; I see no real point in that. If you have userspace to load modules, then<br />&gt; you have userspace to load firmware.<br /><br />David, the case is different: the module is loaded _across_ the <br />suspend/resume, but the device needs to have its firmware reloaded at <br />resume time because it lost power.<br /><br />And since the device may be resumed before the root filesystem disk <br />device, it needs to do so _without_ calling request_firmware() at resume <br />time.<br /><br />The above is _normal_.<br /><br />And the fact is, the only way to handle it sanely is to do the <br />request_firmware() before suspending.<br /><br />I _really_ don't understand why this keeps coming up all the time. It's a <br />no-brainer, with a single possible solution, yet people continue to whine <br />about it.<br /><br />			Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
